cleaning.description: Standardize text columns to uppercase and parse the raw saledate string (which includes timezone abbreviations) into a proper datetime for time-series analysis.
cleaning.code:
# Normalize text fields for consistent grouping
df['make'] = df['make'].str.upper()

# Strip timezone abbreviation suffix, e.g. " (EST)"
cleaned = df['saledate'].str.replace(
    r' \([A-Z]+\)$', '', regex=True
)

# Parse into UTC datetime
df['sale_datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(
    cleaned,
    format='%a %b %d %Y %H:%M:%S GMT%z',
    utc=True, errors='coerce'
)
# Result: 2014-12-16 20:30:00+00:00

category_summary.description: Count transactions per manufacturer to identify which makes dominate auction volume. This is a standard OLAP roll-up from individual rows to category totals.
category_summary.code:
# Group by make -> count rows -> sort descending
tx_by_make = (
    df.groupby('make')
    .size()
    .reset_index(name='transactions')
    .sort_values('transactions', ascending=False)
)
# Top result: FORD — 93,997 transactions

time_summary.description: Aggregate transaction counts by year-month to reveal seasonal patterns and volume trends over time.
time_summary.code:
# Group by year + month for time-series granularity
tx_by_month = (
    df.groupby(['sale_year', 'sale_month'])
    .size()
    .reset_index(name='transactions')
)
# Peak row: 2015-02 | 163,052 transactions

additional_summary.description: Calculate how much each make sells above or below its Manheim Market Report (MMR) value on average. Positive = sellers get more than market estimate.
additional_summary.code:
# Compute per-make average of (sellingprice - mmr)
price_vs_mmr_by_make = (
    df.groupby('make')['price_vs_mmr']
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values('price_vs_mmr', ascending=False)
)
# Insight: most makes sell below MMR (buyer's market)
